SIMPLE: interpose
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interpose
<hw>In`ter*pose"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Interposed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Interposing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>interposer</ets>. See <er>Inter-</er>, and <er>Pose</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To place between; <as>as, to <ex>interpose</ex> a
screen between the eye and the light</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mountains <qex>interposed</qex>⟦br⟧
Make enemies of nations.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To thrust; to intrude; to put between, either for
aid or for troubling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What watchful cares do <qex>interpose</qex> themselves⟦br⟧
Betwixt your eyes and night?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The common Father of mankind seasonably <qex>interposed</qex> his
hand, and rescues miserable man.</q> <rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To introduce or inject between the parts of a
conversation or argument.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interpose</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Interpose
<hw>In`ter*pose"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be or come
between.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Long hid by <qex>interposing</qex> hill or wood.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To step in between parties at variance; to mediate;
<as>as, the prince <ex>interposed</ex> and made peace</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To utter a sentiment by way of interruption.</def>
<rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To intervene; intercede; mediate; interfere;
intermeddle.</syn> <usage> -- To <er>Interpose</er>,
<er>Intermeddle</er>, <er>Interfere</er>. A man may often
<xex>interpose</xex> with propriety in the concerns of others; he can
never <xex>intermeddle</xex> without being impertinent or officious; nor
can be <xex>interfere</xex> without being liable to the same charge,
unless he has rights which are interfered with. ⟦ldquo⟧In our practical
use, <xex>interference</xex> is something offensive. It is the pushing
in of himself between two parties on the part of a third who was not
asked, and is not thanked for his pains, and who, as the feeling of the
word implies, had no business there; while <xex>interposition</xex> is
employed to express the friendly, peacemaking mediation of one whom the
act well became, and who, even if he was not specially invited
thereunto, is still thanked for what he has done.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Trench.</au></usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interpose</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Interpose
<hw>In"ter*pose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<def>Interposition.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interposer</ent>⟦br⟧
